    "long_instructions": "## Do This:\r\n\r\nYou're designing a simple program to simulate a productive study session. The code includes repeated reminders to take breaks and check your to-do list, but it's messy and hard to maintain. Clean things up by writing two functions that organize these tasks.\r\n\r\n1. Look closely at the code. There are **two different blocks** of repeated code:\r\n\r\n   * One reminds you to take a break.\r\n   \r\n   * One tells you to check your to-do list.\r\n\r\n2. Define a function called `take_break()` for the break reminders.\r\n\r\n3. Define a second function called `check_todo()` for the to-do list reminders.\r\n\r\n4. Replace the repeated blocks by calling your new functions in the correct places.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-laptop\"></i> **Coding Tip**\r\n\r\nEach function should include the lines that belong together. Pay close attention to indentation, and use the UMPIRE strategy:\r\n\r\n* **U**nderstand: What's repeated and why?\r\n\r\n* **M**ake a plan: Which messages go in which function?\r\n\r\n* **P**roduce: Write and call both functions.\r\n\r\n* **I**nspect: Does it run as expected?\r\n\r\n* **E**xplain: How did using functions improve the code?",
